isfaction, how they succeed and fail, and how the rhythms of their work change as they age. His candid interviews with his subjects, meanwhile, shed light on the ways career goals are and are not met, on the frustrations of the academic profession, and on how one deals with the boredom and stagnation that can set in once one is established. An in-depth study of American higher education professionals eloquently told through their own words, Hermanowicz’s keen analysis of how institutions shape careers will appeal to anyone interested in life in academia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDialogue analysisxSocial aspects. 0aDiscourse analysis, NarrativexSocial aspects. 0aNarrationxSocial aspects. 0aStorytellingxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  asociology, sociological, sociologists, science, academics, academic careers, institutions, institutional structures, professional lives, profession, jobs, labor, work, physicist, physics, professors, university, school, american higher education, united states of america, usa, vocations, vocational guidance, social aspects, theoretical perspectives, fieldwork, life course, scientists.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022632761740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226327761423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226327761/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles